  "prompt": "How do you say \"I hate when that happens\" in French?",
  "response": "There are several ways to say \"I hate when that happens\" in French, depending on the context and the level of formality you want to use. Here are a few options:\n\n**Common & Versatile Options:**\n\n*   **Je d\u00e9teste quand \u00e7a arrive.** (I detest when that happens.) - This is a very direct translation and works in most situations.\n*   **Je d\u00e9teste quand \u00e7a fait \u00e7a.** (I detest when it does that.) - This is a common and slightly more idiomatic way of saying it, especially when referring to a machine or object acting up.\n*   **\u00c7a m'\u00e9nerve quand \u00e7a arrive.** (It annoys me when that happens.) - \"\u00c9nerver\" is a good word to use for things that are irritating.\n*   **\u00c7a m'agace quand \u00e7a arrive.** (It irritates me when that happens.) - Similar to \"\u00e9nerver,\" but perhaps a slightly milder tone.\n\n**More Informal Options:**\n\n*   **\u00c7a me gave quand \u00e7a arrive.** (It disgusts me when that happens.) - \"Gaver\" is a very informal term and implies a feeling of being fed up or disgusted. Use it with people you know well.\n*   **\u00c7a me saoule quand \u00e7a arrive.** (It bores/tires me when that happens.) - \"Saouler\" literally means \"to get drunk,\" but colloquially it means \"to bore or tire someone.\" This is also fairly informal.\n*   **Putain, je d\u00e9teste quand \u00e7a arrive!** (Damn, I hate when that happens!) - Adds emphasis, but use with caution depending on the context and who you are speaking with.\n\n**More Specific Options (depending on the context):**\n\n*   **Je d\u00e9teste quand \u00e7a se produit.** (I detest when that occurs.) - Similar to \"arrive\" but a little more formal.\n*   **Je d\u00e9teste quand on fait \u00e7a.** (I hate when people do that.) - Use this when you are referring to a specific action someone does.\n\n**Which one should you use?**\n\n*   For most situations, **\"Je d\u00e9teste quand \u00e7a arrive\"** or **\"\u00c7a m'\u00e9nerve quand \u00e7a arrive\"** are good choices.\n*   Consider the formality of the situation. If you are speaking with a close friend, \"\u00c7a me gave quand \u00e7a arrive\" might be appropriate. If you are speaking in a professional setting, \"Je d\u00e9teste quand \u00e7a se produit\" might be a better choice.\n\nThe best choice depends on the nuance you want to convey and your relationship with the person you're talking to.\n",
